Introduction

The Great Lakes are a major source of water, recreation, and industry for over 30 million people, including most Michigan residents. However, in recent years, there has been a growing concern over steadily rising water levels: news sources such as the Green Bay Press-Gazette, the Detroit Free Press, and The Washington Post have highlighted the resulting property damage, shoreline erosion, and economic disruption. As such, environmental scientists have been investigating the potential causes and implications of high water in the Great Lakes, tying this into the larger conversation about climate change.

In this project, we consider the variation in water levels in Lake Michigan-Huron over the time period \(????\)-2021.

include goals and objectives here

NB: Lake Michigan and Lake Huron are hydrologically one lake, since the flow of water through the Straits of Mackinac keeps their respective water levels in near-equilibrium.

Data

The data consists of monthly lake level means and was downloaded from the Great Lakes Environmental Research Laboratory (GLERL), an arm of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA). We plot the data below.
